<http://www.ae.iastate.edu/aen125.htm>

"Carbon monoxide (CO) and carbon dioxide (CO2) are produced 1) when
fossil fuels are burned, 2) from cigarette smoke, and 3) from human and=20=

animal respiration.=A0 Carbon monoxide is odorless, colorless, and =
highly=20
toxic.=A0 It kills by reducing the oxygen supply in the body and is a=20
deadly poison.=A0 It adversely affects human health at only a few parts=20=

per million and causes death at 250 parts per million (250 ppm).

Properly installed and maintained heating appliances cause little threat=20=

from carbon monoxide.=A0 Poorly installed and maintained systems can be=20=

deadly.=A0 All fossil fuels contain carbon.=A0 During the combustion =
process=20
the carbon in the fuel combines with oxygen in the air.=A0 With =
sufficient=20
oxygen, sufficient turbulence, and at high ignition temperatures, nearly=20=

all of the carbon combines with two atoms of oxygen, producing the=20
relatively innocuous carbon dioxide.=A0 Heating appliances are designed =
to=20
provide excess oxygen, and a clean, properly installed and maintained=20
system will produce primarily carbon dioxide (CO2), a large amount of=20
water vapor, small amounts of carbon monoxide (CO), and a number of=20
other pollutants.=A0 These products of combustion from a properly=20
maintained heating system will be vented outdoors through the chimney,=20=

and do not pose an undue risk to the building occupants."

